'''Cantagiro''' was an Italian summer festival held from 1962 to 1972 and 1990 to 1993. It featured three categories, A for famous artists, B for newcomers and C for groups. The creator of the competition was [[Ezio Radaelli]]. The name of the festival was a reference to the [[Bicycle racing|bicycle race]] [[Giro d'Italia]], and, as the Giro, Cantagiro was organized as a [[stage race]] consisting of eleven or twelve daily stages, each set in a different city.<ref name=hd>{{cite book|last=Felice Liperi|title=Storia della canzone italiana|publisher=RAI-ERI, 1999|isbn=8839710647}}</ref><ref name=hhd>{{cite book|last=Aldo Grasso|title=Radio e televisione|publisher=Vita e Pensiero, 2000|isbn=8834305787}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Gianfranco Salvatore|title=L'arcobaleno: storia vera di Lucio Battisti vissuta da Mogol e dagli altri che c'erano|publisher=Giunti Editore, 2000|isbn=8809018052|pages=16–17}}</ref> A peculiar characteristic of the festival was that, while traveling between one stage and the other, singers were required to travel in an open car, to be at the disposal of the crowd of fans, otherwise risking fines or disqualification from the competition; accordingly the travel usually resolved into a huge crowd, with fans waiting their idols in every corner of the path.<ref name="hd"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Claudia Provvedini|title=Morto Ezio Radaelli inventore del Cantagiro e "patron" di Sanremo|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2005/ottobre/16/Morto_Ezio_Radaelli_inventore_del_co_9_051016020.shtml|accessdate=4 November 2013|newspaper=[[Corriere della Sera]]|date=16 October 2005}}</ref>
The festival was the main subject of two [[musicarello]] films, ''Urlo contro melodia nel Cantagiro 1963'' (1964) and ''La più bella coppia del mondo'' (1967).<ref>{{cite book|last=Roberto Poppi, Mario Pecorari|title=Dizionario del cinema italiano. I film|publisher=Gremese Editore, 2007|isbn=8884405033}}</ref>
