'''Corporatocracy''' ({{IPAc-en|ˌ|k|ɔr|p|ə|r|ə|ˈ|t|ɒ|k|r|ə|s|i}}, from '[[corporate]]' and {{lang-el|-κρατία|translit=-kratía|lit=domination by}}, short form '''corpocracy''',<ref>https://wordspy.com/index.php?word=corpocracy    corpocracy   n. A society in which corporations have substantial economic and political power.</ref> is a recent{{when|date=October 2018}} term used to refer to an economic and political system controlled by [[corporation]]s or corporate interests.<ref name="oxford dictionary">{{cite news|title= Corporatocracy|newspaper= Oxford Dictionaries|url= http://oxforddictionaries.com/definition/corporatocracy|accessdate= May 29, 2012}}</ref> It is most often used as a term to describe the economic situation in a particular country.<ref name="reysen boston globe">{{cite news |author= Jamie Reysen |title= At Boston's Dewey Square, a protest of varied voices |publisher= ''Boston Globe'' |quote= ... Corporatocracy is the new Fascism ... |date= October 4, 2011 |url= http://articles.boston.com/2011-10-04/yourtown/30243272_1_protesters-plan-hundred-protesters-tent |accessdate= 2012-01-04}}</ref><ref name="storey new york times">{{cite news |author= Will Storey |title= D.C. Occupied, More or Less |publisher= ''The New York Times'' |quote= ... we’ve surrendered our nation to a corporatocracy ... |date= October 6, 2011 |url= http://thecaucus.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/10/06/d-c-occupied-more-or-less/ |accessdate= 2012-01-04}}</ref> This is different from [[corporatism]], which is the organisation of society into groups with common interests. Corporatocracy as a term is often used by observers across the political spectrum.<ref>
