The '''Hult Prize''' was established in 2010 by Ahmad Ashkar and [[Bertil Hult]],<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/bertil-hult/ | publisher=Forbes | title=Profile - Bertil Hult}}</ref> and is an annual, year-long competition that crowd-sources ideas from MBA and college students after challenging them to solve a pressing social issue around topics such as food security, water access, energy, and education.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/jonathan-littman/milliondollar-hunger-real_b_2814157.html Million dollar hunger reality show: The Hult Prize], Huffington Post, 3/7/2013</ref> The Hult family – founders of EF Education First – donates USD 1 million in seed capital to help the winning team launch a social enterprise.<ref>[https://www.bostonglobe.com/business/2013/02/03/founder-bertil-hult-sees-education-first-breaking-down-global-barriers/KK6hpFwDqvocR73w0Xf9jO/story.html Education First aims to bridge barriers with exchange], Boston Globe, 2/4/2013</ref> 

The Prize is a partnership between [[Hult International Business School]] and the [[United Nations Foundation]]. [[Bill Clinton]] selects the challenge topic and announces the winner each September;{{cn|date=September 2018}} he mentioned it in a 2012 ''[[TIME Magazine]]'' article about "the top 5 ideas that are changing the world for the better".<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,2125031-6,00.html The case for optimism], TIME Magazine, 10/1/2012</ref>

== History ==
In 2009, Ahmad Ashkar left the banking industry during the economic downturn to pursue an MBA at [[Hult International Business School]].<ref name="bloomberg">[https://www.bloomberg.com/video/creating-the-next-wave-of-social-entrepreneurs-mKQuhLy4QHSokxb1~JOEcQ.html Creating the next wave of social entrepreneurs], Ahmad Ashkar appearance on Bloomberg TV’s Taking Stock with Pimm Fox, 5/30/2013</ref> A lecture given by [[One Laptop Per Child]] director Chuck Kane introduced Ashkar to the concept of social entrepreneurship and sparked his idea for the Hult Prize (originally called the Hult Global Case Challenge).<ref name="bloomberg" /> In 2013, the Prize attracted more than 10,000 MBA and undergraduate applicants.<ref>http://video.foxnews.com/v/2421703863001/, Ahmad Ashkar appearance on Fox News, 5/30/2013.</ref>

== Partnerships ==
In 2010, the competition focused on education in partnership with One Laptop Per Child.<ref>[http://www.chinastakes.com/2010/2/top-business-students-to-compete-for-innovative-solution-to-educate-2-billion-poor-kids.html Top business school students to compete for innovative solution to educate 2 billion poor kids] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101030002208/http://www.chinastakes.com/2010/2/top-business-students-to-compete-for-innovative-solution-to-educate-2-billion-poor-kids.html |date=2010-10-30 }}, Chinastakes.com, 2/25/2010</ref> The 2011 event partnered with [[water.org]] to focus on the provision of clean water.<ref>[http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8c9679f4-f0b0-11df-8cc5-00144feab49a.html Matt Damon’s charity benefits from global MBA advice], Financial Times, 11/15/2010</ref>

