{{Infobox | abovestyle = background:#E9967A; | above = List of industrial festivals | image = [[File:Militia Maschinenfest 4.jpg|260px]] | caption = | headerstyle = background:#EDC9AF; | header1 = General Information | label2 = Related genres | data2 = [[Industrial music]], [[electro-industrial]], [[Electronic body music|EBM]], [[industrial rock]], [[industrial metal]] | label3 = Location | data3 = Worldwide | label4 = Related events | data4 = [[Concert tour]], [[music festival]], [[heavy metal festivals]], [[EDM festivals]], [[goth festivals]], [[rock festivals]], [[punk festivals]] | label5 = Related topics | data5 = [[Cassette culture]], [[rivethead]], [[steampunk]], [[list of industrial music bands|industrial music bands]] }} The following is an '''incomplete list of industrial music festivals,''' which encapsulates [[music festivals]] focused on [[industrial music]]. The list may have some overlap with [[list of electronic music festivals]], [[list of gothic festivals]], and [[list of heavy metal festivals]]. Industrial music is a genre of [[experimental music]] that draws on transgressive and provocative themes. The term was coined in the mid-1970s,<ref>"... journalists now use 'industrial' as a term like they would 'blues.'"—Genesis P-Orridge, ''RE/Search'' #6/7, p. 16.</ref> and precursors included acts such as [[electronic music|electronic]] group [[Kraftwerk]], [[experimental rock]] acts such as [[The Velvet Underground]] and [[Frank Zappa]], [[psychedelic rock]] artists such as [[Jimi Hendrix]], and composers such as [[John Cage]]. [[AllMusic]] defines industrial as the "most abrasive and aggressive fusion of rock and electronic music"; "initially a blend of avant-garde electronics experiments (tape music, [[musique concrète]], white noise, synthesizers, sequencers, etc.) and [[punk rock|punk]] provocation".<ref>{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=explore|id=style/d141|pure_url=yes}}|title=Industrial|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation|accessdate=October 27, 2009}}</ref>
Notable hybrid genres are [[industrial rock]] from the late 1970s and [[industrial metal]] from the 1980s, while [[electro-industrial]] developed in the late 1980s. Because of its genre fluidity, industrial music may be featured at [[rock festivals]], [[heavy metal festivals]], [[goth festivals]], and [[electronic music festivals]], though there are also festivals dedicated solely to industrial music. In North America in particular, electro-industrial music is often termed [[industrial dance]], and since the late 1980s industrial music festivals often attract industrial fans termed [[rivethead]]s or [[cybergoths]],<ref name="cyber">{{cite book | title=ECO-TEC: Architecture of the In-Between - | publisher=Princeton Architectural Press | author=Marras, Amerigo | year=1999 | pages=54 | isbn=1568981597}}</ref> with other countercultures such as [[cyberpunk]] and [[goth]] appearing as well. Cybergoth dance styles include [[rave dance|rave dance styles]], while more rock-focused festivals may feature dance styles such as [[pogo (dance)|pogoing]], [[headbanging]], and [[moshing]]. The rivethead dress code that emerged in the late 1980s<ref name=steele>Steele, Valerie (2008). Gothic: Dark Glamour. Yale University Press. p. 48.</ref> is [[militaristic]] with hints of [[Punk fashion|punk aesthetics]] and [[fetish fashion]],<ref name="undead69">Lauren M. E. Goodlad, Michael Bibby: ''Goth. Undead subculture'', Duke University Press, 2007, {{ISBN|978-0822339212}}, p. 69</ref> while cybergoth fashion from the late 1990s combines rivethead industrial aesthetics with a style associated with "gravers" (gothic ravers).<ref name=steele/>
